{
  "_comment": [
    "Owner's manual track-stitching observations (2026-07-13 session), watched",
    "in the designer replay across five captures. Abbreviated on-screen ids",
    "(last-4-digit suffixes) were resolved to full raw oids by suffix match",
    "against each capture's oid inventory; every resolution was unique.",
    "",
    "kind semantics (owner's words):",
    "  handoff     - different sensors' views of the same object -> must end up",
    "                one fused track.",
    "  persistence - one sensor dropped and re-acquired the same object under a",
    "                new id -> must end up one fused track.",
    "  anchor      - a track the owner observed persisting correctly through a",
    "                long red-light stop under ONE id; it must not absorb any",
    "                same-sensor neighbour (queue-mate) - cross-sensor fusion of",
    "                the same vehicle is fine.",
    "  stray       - not a genuine object (interference / 'shadow' of a real",
    "                vehicle); must not merge into any genuine group.",
    "'unsure': owner could not confirm by eye; scored separately, and the",
    "engine's verdict on these is reported back rather than gated.",
    "'ped': the object is a pedestrian.",
    "'same_sensor': owner marked * or the members share a slot - the mechanism",
    "is within-sensor stitching even when listed under handoff.",
    "'fused_refs': small integers the owner wrote that are not raw oids; they",
    "match no oid in the capture and are believed to be fused-view ids from the",
    "designer's fused toggle (resolved/validated by the eval harness, not gated).",
    "",
    "Slots >= 4 are the vendor's combined-object ids: when the vendor itself",
    "decides two sensors' objects are one vehicle it retires BOTH raw ids and",
    "continues the object under a freshly allocated id + 4 (623980 -> 623984,",
    "slot 4 = sensor 0's counter, slot 5 = sensor 1's), cls 0. The combined",
    "track starts the frame after its members end - zero temporal overlap."
  ],
